Background¶

We'll be looking at data about teams in Major League Baseball from 1990 - 2014.

Major League Baseball is a professional baseball league, where teams pay players to play baseball. The goal of each team is to win as many games out of a 162 game season as possible. Teams win games by scoring more runs (getting more points) than their adversary.

In principle, better players are costlier, so teams that want good players need to spend more money. Teams that spend the most, frequently win the most. So, the question is, how can a team that can't spend so much win?

The basic idea that the Oakland A's (and other teams) used is to redefine what makes a player good, such as figuring out what player characteristics translated into wins. Once they realized that teams were not really pricing players using these characteristics, they could exploit this to pay for undervalued players, players that were good according to their metrics, but were not recognized as such by other teams, and therefore not as expensive.

You can get more information about this period in baseball history from:

Moneyball Wiki

Moneyball Book

Moneyball Movie

Data Collection¶

About the Data¶

We'll be using data from a useful database on baseball teams, players, and seasons curated by Sean Lahman available at http://www.seanlahman.com/baseball-archive/statistics/.

The database is available as a sqlite database https://github.com/jknecht/baseball-archive-sqlite, which will be used for this project.

Sqlite is a light-weight, file-based database management system that is well suited for small projects and prototypes.

You can read more about the dataset here: http://seanlahman.com/files/database/readme2014.txt.

Part 1: Wrangling¶

Access sqlite file to extract the Salaries and Teams tables of the database.

In [2]:
sqlite_file = 'lahman2014.sqlite'
conn = sql.connect(sqlite_file)

Both separate dataframes will be grouped by team and year and ordered (ascending) by team.

Create dataframe from the Salaries table using data involving team, year, and total_payroll (sum of salaries).

In [3]:
salary_query = "SELECT teamID as team, yearID as year, sum(salary) as total_payroll FROM Salaries GROUP BY teamId, yearID ORDER BY teamID"
team_salaries = pd.read_sql(salary_query, conn)

Create dataframe from the Teams table using data involving team, year, wins, games, winning_percentage (wins / games * 100), and franchise.

In [4]:
winning_query = "SELECT teamID as team, yearID as year, W as wins, G as games, W * 100.0 / G as winning_percentage, franchID as franchise FROM Teams GROUP BY teamID, yearID ORDER BY teamID"
team_winnings = pd.read_sql(winning_query, conn)

Join both dataframes into one by team and year.

By performing Inner Join, any missing data between both dataframes via team and year will be ignored.

In [5]:
team_results = pd.merge(team_salaries, team_winnings, how='inner', on=['team','year'])

Analysis¶

Based on the graph above, payrolls across teams had increased over time between 1990 to 2014. Not only that, each team experienced a greater variance in their payrolls, which makes it more difficult to sprecifically predit how much they'll spend in the future. Across all the teams, there's a very high range of payrolls, as viewed by the increasing spread between each line, but there is a clear statement that teams are spending more on average over time.

2.c Correlation Between Payroll & Winning Percentage¶

Using the data that's been condition from 1990 to 2014, a new column is created that indicates a four year period that a specific row belongs to.

In [11]:
new_data = data_condition.copy()

periods = ['1990 - 1994','1995 - 1999','2000 - 2004','2005 - 2009','2010 - 2014']
new_data['period'] = pd.cut(new_data['year'], bins = 5, right = False, labels = periods)

For each period, plot a scatterplot that represents the average winning percentage (y-axis) over average payroll (x-axis) of all teams that competed that period.

Each point on the graph will be labeled and a regression line will be added for future interpretation.

In [12]:
# 5 periods
for period in periods:
    # select a specific period throughout the table
    section_data = new_data[new_data.period == period]
    
    # get the values of each teams average payroll and average winnings
    avg_payroll = section_data.groupby('team')['total_payroll'].mean().values
    avg_win = section_data.groupby('team')['winning_percentage'].mean().values
    
    # create a dataframe of both values
    table = pd.DataFrame({'team': section_data['team'].drop_duplicates().values, 'avg_payroll': avg_payroll, 'avg_win': avg_win})
    
    # scatterplot w/ regression line
    plt.figure(figsize = (10, 10))
    m, b = np.polyfit(table['avg_payroll'], table['avg_win'], 1)
    plt.plot(table['avg_payroll'], m * table['avg_payroll'] + b)
    plt.scatter(table['avg_payroll'], table['avg_win'])
 
    # label each point on the graph with their respective team
    for index, txt in enumerate(table['team']):
        plt.annotate(txt, (table.at[index, 'avg_payroll'], table.at[index, 'avg_win']))
      
    # label the graph with a title, x-axis, and y-axis
    plt.title(period, fontsize = 16)
    plt.xlabel("Average Payroll ($)", fontsize = 14)
    plt.ylabel("Average Winning Percentage (%)", fontsize = 14)
    plt.show()

Analysis¶

Across all four year periods, there's a common trend which indicates that the higher the average payroll, the higher the winning percentage. Based off this observation, we can say that teams that were placed above the regression line were more efficient in spending money for wins than those under the regression line.

Apart from 2005 - 2009, ATL seemed to standout as being particularly good at paying for wins across these periods. NYA, in particular, spends the most money than any other teams and still gets a high winning percentage.

In all five periods, Oakland A stayed above the regression line, which indicates that they've been efficient in spending money for wins. On top of that, Oakland A generally doesn't spend that much compared to other teams above the regression line. Oakland A would especially be very effective in spending less but still winning more during 2000 - 2004.

Part 3: Data transformations¶

3.a Standardizing Across Years¶

By finding the average payroll and standard deviation of all teams in a given year, the standardized payroll of a team from a particular year is calculated and stored in the main dataframe.

In [13]:
avg_payroll = new_data.groupby('year')['total_payroll'].mean()
std = new_data.groupby('year')['total_payroll'].std()

for index, row in new_data.iterrows():
    new_data.at[index, 'stdz_payroll'] = (row['total_payroll'] - avg_payroll[row['year']]) / std[row['year']]

# main dataframe

Analysis¶

Both plots from above and Section 2.c have an increasing regression line. With this new information, it can be said that the more standard deviations above the average payroll of all teams spent will result in more winnings. In other words, the higher above the average payroll of all teams spent, the higher the winnings.

To touch back on Oakland A's example from 2000 - 20004, even though they spent almost one standard deviation below the average payroll of all the teams that period, they were still able to achieve a high winning percentage than almost all the teams.

Concluding Analysis¶

Although spending more on players will predictably result in more wins, concluded from sections 2.c and 3.a, it doesn't necessarily mean that it's efficient all the time. This can be seen by the high range of fluctations of efficiency from the graph above and, most notably, Oakland's efficiency during the Moneyball period (2000 - 2005).

Oakland's efficiency was the highest for a considerable time during the Moneyball period. This goes to show that effectively spending money on the right players rather than spending more money overall can go a long way and end up bring the team more wins.
